  "prompt": "What is Foot & Mouth Disease (FMD)?",
  "response": "**Foot-and-Mouth Disease (FMD)** is a highly contagious viral disease that affects cloven-hoofed animals, including cattle, pigs, sheep, goats, and deer. It is caused by the **Foot-and-Mouth Disease Virus (FMDV)**, which belongs to the *Picornaviridae* family. FMD is not typically fatal in adult animals but can cause severe economic losses due to its impact on livestock productivity and trade restrictions.\n\n### Key Features of FMD:\n1. **Symptoms**:\n   - Fever\n   - Blisters or sores on the mouth, tongue, lips, and feet\n   - Excessive salivation and drooling\n   - Lameness or reluctance to move\n   - Reduced milk production in dairy animals\n   - Weight loss and poor growth in young animals\n\n2. **Transmission**:\n   - The virus spreads through direct contact with infected animals, contaminated equipment, feed, or clothing.\n   - It can also be transmitted via aerosols (airborne particles) over short distances.\n   - Humans can inadvertently carry the virus on their clothing or shoes.\n\n3. **Economic Impact**:\n   - FMD is a major concern for livestock industries worldwide due to its rapid spread and the trade bans it triggers.\n   - Infected animals experience reduced productivity, and outbreaks can lead to mass culling to control the disease.\n\n4. **Prevention and Control**:\n   - **Vaccination**: Vaccines are available but must be matched to the specific strain of the virus.\n   - **Biosecurity**: Strict measures to prevent the introduction and spread of the virus, such as quarantines, disinfection, and movement controls.\n   - **Surveillance**: Early detection and reporting of outbreaks are critical.\n\n5. **Human Health**:\n   - FMD is not considered a threat to human health, as humans are rarely infected. When it does occur, it is mild and self-limiting.\n\nFMD is endemic in certain parts of the world, particularly in Africa, Asia, and South America. Countries free of FMD often implement stringent import regulations to protect their livestock populations.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
